T1  - The elasticity of substitution in India's manufacturing sector
AU  - Laumas, Prem S.
AU  - Williams, Martin
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 8
IS  - 3
SP  - 325
EP  - 337
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(81)90019-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387881900195
AB  - Using cross-section data and the translog cost function this paper examines the substitution possibilities between capital and materials and labor and materials since raw materials might be used to overcome the bottlenecks caused by shortages of physical capital and skilled labor. Three significant conclusions are: (a) Since materials are substitutable for both capital and labor to a considerable extent, capital and skilled labor may not be a binding constraint on growth. Agricultural materials expansion may substitute for these inputs and lead to expansion in the industrial sector. (b) Fixed proportion models are not warranted in India without modification, and (c) separability tests showed that materials must be included in the production function.
